<dl id="n09086k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09086k">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09086k"> 86(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Historic Doubts respecting / N&mdash; B&mdash; / Whately 1826</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>Literature and Life. The Propogandist as Myth-Maker</b> &hellip; Five years after Waterloo, the future Archbishop <mark>Whately had written his <cite>Historic Doubts Relative to Napoleon Buonaparte</cite></mark> to show that the discrepancies between the alleged facts and the actual evidence made the whole story so fantastic as to strain honest belief. <small> <a name="IS1mar24" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#IS1mar24"><cite title="source">Irish Statesman</cite></a> (1 March 1924) 782ff</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: A reference to Richard Whately, <cite>Historic Doubts relative to Napoleon Buonaparte</cite> (London, 1819) <br>Raphael transcription: <a name="c03116k" href="c03all.htm#c03116k">VI.C.03:116(k)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
